<p>For the starting date of a zodiac year, there are two schools of thought=
 in Chinese astrology: <a href=3D"https://www.chinahighlights.com/travelgui=
de/festivals/when-chinese-new-year.htm">Chinese New Year</a> or the Start o=
f Spring.</p>

<ul class=3D"drop1">
	<li><strong>Chinese New Year</strong>, day 1 of the Chinese lunar year, fa=
lls somewhere in the period January 21<sup>st</sup> to February 20<sup>th</=
sup>.</li>
	<li><strong>The Start of Spring</strong> is the 1<sup>st</sup> of the <a h=
ref=3D"https://www.chinahighlights.com/festivals/the-24-solar-terms.htm">24=
 Solar Terms</a>, beginning on February 3<sup>rd</sup> or 4<sup>th</sup>.</=
li>
</ul>

<p>Most Chinese people use Chinese New Year as the start of the zodiac year=
. This is popular Chinese astrology. Only traditionalists and professional =
astrologers use the first solar term. Therefore, for example if you were <s=
trong>born in January or February</strong> in 1997, you might be an Ox or a=
 Rat.</p>

